<div class="intro"><h2>hello AnonymousUser98</h2>
	<div class="divider"></div>
	<p>to begin with, you're a dumbass</p>
	</div>
		<p>“free” does not mean public domain. a free app is still copyrighted. a free system component is still copyrighted. a bios was not “free” just because it came inside a device you bought. you bought access to a device containing software. you did not receive a divine mandate to collect copies of that software from whatever zip file xXx_NeTWaReZKiNg_xXx uploaded in 2011.</p>

		<p>“owned” does not mean “entitled to any copy from anywhere.” if you dump your own game, from your own media, for your own use, that is the cleanest practical position. it may still live in a messy legal grey zone depending on jurisdiction, circumvention, license terms, and the specific facts, but at least the provenance is not complete fairy dust. downloading someone else’s rom because you own a cartridge is different. the bits may be identical. the source is not. the chain of authorisation is not. the law is famously uninterested in your metaphysical bit-identical soul bond with a cartridge in a drawer.</p>

		<p>“preservation” also does not mean “i wanted it.” actual preservation is a serious issue. it involves archives, libraries, controlled access, documentation, provenance, and legal frameworks that are still painfully inadequate. it does not become preservation because kyle from a forum slapped 7z on a directory and called it “no-intro”. that may be useful. it may even be culturally defensible in some cases. it is not automatically lawful, and it is absolutely not a clean basis for a homebrew support community to build policy around.</p>

		<p>the “no harm” argument is similarly adorable. harm matters ethically. harm can matter legally. harm is not the entire definition of infringement. copyright is not only a tip jar for currently employed developers. it is a bundle of rights around copying, distribution, adaptation, and access. you can think the bundle is too broad. you can think enforcement is abusive. you can think abandonware should have a sane legal pathway. fine. congratulations, you have discovered policy criticism. you have not discovered that downloading commercial games becomes legal when your vibes are sufficiently moist.</p>

		<p>rom hacks are another overclaimed mess. a patch that contains only original changes and requires the user to supply their own rom is generally much cleaner than distributing a modified full rom. that does not make every rom hack “perfectly legal.” derivative works are a thing. fair use is a thing. both are fact-specific. “for personal enjoyment” is not a magic spell. it is barely even a sentence.</p>

		<p>and then there is the community-rule argument: “do not discriminate against pirates." to which the response is: how about no<br>
		a homebrew community is not a court. it is not required to litigate every user’s personal mythology about where their files came from. it is allowed to say: we do not help with downloaded games, unauthorised copies, title keys, warez, bios files, piracy tools, or any troubleshooting path that depends on pretending nobody knows what is happening. that's hygiene, not "discrimination".</p>

		<p>you can have whatever files you want on your own sd card. you can tell yourself whatever bedtime story you need. but when you ask a public community for help, the community gets to decide what it will touch. “i already paid for it” does not obligate anyone else to help you make an unauthorised copy work. “nintendo is bad” does not turn a support channel into a rom concierge. “it is for preservation” does not mean “please debug my stolen cia.”</p>

		<p>the practical rule remains simple:<br>
		if you dumped your own copy and still possess the original, you are in the least stupid position.<br>
		if you downloaded a commercial game from the internet, that is piracy for community purposes.<br>
		if you downloaded firmware, bios files, paid software, delisted software, or “free” proprietary software from unofficial sources, that is still unauthorised access and/or distribution for community (and often legal) purposes.<br>
		if you distribute dumps, title keys, full rom hacks, prepatched roms, or instructions designed to obtain copyrighted software without authorisation, that is piracy support.<br>
		if your argument requires three paragraphs of ethical fog before you can say where the file came from, the file came from the piracy dimension.</p>

		<p>the goal is not to crown nintendo king of morality. the goal is to keep homebrew separate from warez, because homebrew survives by being defensible. console hacking, user control, repair, preservation, modding, and interoperability are all worth defending. they become much harder to defend when every discussion is immediately colonised by someone insisting their downloaded pokemon rom is actually civil disobedience because they bought a cartridge in 2007.</p>

		<p>the protest page IS correct about exactly one thing: the law is complicated.<br>
		ironically that's also why “it’s not piracy!!!” is such a dumb title.</p>
